JIRA: https://track.akamai.com/jira/browse/CEPH-174

Developer: @vgoot
Code Review: @sung @kkeshava

[Description]
  Abort PCONN on 4xx error when expect-100-continue included in HTTP header

[Output]
log output are added to note PCONN termination and delay 
  ldout(cct, 5) << "PCONN abort on error delayed: " << delay_ms << dendl;
  ldout(cct, 1) << "PCONN abort on error enforced" << dendl;

[Config]
name: rgw_request_close_conn_on_error_override
  type: bool
  level: dev
  default: false
  desc: Force the connection to close by overriding the keep-alive option when an error occurs (e.g., HTTP response code is in the 4xx range).
  long_desc: JIRA https://track.akamai.com/jira/browse/CEPH-174
    When this value is set to false, keep-alive for such requests functions as intended.
    When this value is set to true, it will abort requests that include the Expect-100-Continue header, operate in keep-alive mode and end up with an error.
    This is essentially an Akamai workaround for the OSPROXY solution, which forwards the payload along with the Expect-100-Continue header
    because it cannot decouple the signature logic from the HTTP connection control logic.
    This behavior confuses RGW, as it does not expect both the Expect-100-Continue header and the payload to be present simultaneously in the request.
    While this setup does not pose an issue when such requests succeed, as RGW will process the payload normally, it causes problems in error scenarios.
    In the event of an error, RGW does not discard the residual payload that OSPROXY sends prematurely, leading to the failure of the next request
    on the same PCONN because the residual payload is not cleaned up.
    Note that the vast majority of clients are designed to wait for an acknowledgment before sending the payload.
    The negative impacts become evident when OSPROXY is part of the chain. If OSPROXY is removed from the architecture, this patch can be safely rolled back.
  services:
  - rgw
name: rgw_request_close_conn_on_error_delay
  type: int
  level: dev
  default: 0
  desc:  Adds a delay to penalize clients before aborting requests that encounter an error.
  long_desc: JIRA https://track.akamai.com/jira/browse/CEPH-174
     This setting only takes effect when rgw_request_close_conn_on_error_override is set to true and applies to requests that include the Expect-100-Continue header,
     operate in keep-alive mode, and result in an error.
     A value of 0 means no additional delay is added.
     A positive value introduces a delay (in milliseconds) before the PCONN is aborted (bounded up to 10 sec). 
     The delay is intended to slow down clients that trigger 4xx responses, mitigating potential abuse where a malicious client disrupts normal operations.
     By delaying connection closure, the server reduces the overhead associated with establishing new connections, thereby conserving resources and maintaining stability.
  services:
  - rgw
  see_also:
  - rgw_request_close_conn_on_error_override

[Notes]
Aborting persistent connections introduces overhead associated with establishing new connections. To address this, configurable delay option is added to penalize clients 
generating 4xx traffic before aborting such requests. Adding delay on the RGW side obviously isn't ideal, since it ties up PCONN resources.

To evaluate the potential impact, of PCONN termination we can add Grafana dashboard to track the rate of 4xx versus 2xx response codes in production. 
This data can be extracted from the OSPROXY access logs available in Grafana. Under normal circumstances, traffic should predominantly result in 2xx responses. 
We should define a threshold and set up an alert based on the 2xx to 4xx response ratio. For example, a ratio of 1:1000 may be acceptable, 
but anything lower could indicate potential issues, such as an ongoing attack or a severe client misconfiguration.

The primary purpose of the proxy, which is to protect the backend, is not functioning as intended in the current OSPROXY setup, 
as it forwards the payload without waiting for an ACK from the server. This exposes the system to potential attacks. 
The proposed solution should be treated as a temporary workaround while transitioning to Envoy.

[Rollout]
Feature is disabled by default,
to abort connection on error set rgw_request_close_conn_on_error_override to true
to enable 1 second timeout before abort set rgw_request_close_conn_on_error_delay to 1000 (max is bounded to 10 sec) 

With this approach:
The feature will be automatically disabled in Gen2 clusters.
For Gen1 clusters, SREs will need to manually enable the feature as required.

